Genre: 2D Pixel-Art Narrative Co-op Adventure
 Engine: Unity (Steam + Online Co-op)
 Players: 2 (Human / Ghost)
 Theme: Connection between life and death; fleeting cooperation; light versus shadow

Premise
Every midnight, a forgotten subway beneath the city becomes a passageway between worlds.
 One traveler is alive — a commuter trapped underground.
 The other is a wandering ghost, bound to the tunnels since the accident that took her life.
 For sixty seconds each night, their worlds overlap.
 During that short time, they must work together to find the way out — or be lost to the rails forever.
Human is sorta a lost soul, not knowing why they're in the metro station in the first place, has to work with ghosts to find their fragments of memories and help the ghost escape.

Gameplay Overview
Dual-World Exploration
 Each player sees a different version of the same map: the Human World (physical) and the Spirit World (ethereal).
Timed “Midnight Merge”
Once per in-game cycle, the worlds align for 60 seconds. During this merge, both players can see and interact with the same objects.
Co-op Puzzles
 Progress requires both roles: the Human manipulates physical levers and electricity; the Ghost passes through walls to reveal hidden paths or memories.
Shared Fate System
 Health and progress are linked — if one is harmed or lost, both fade. Teamwork is essential.
Echoes and Memories
 Collect Echo Fragments — short pixel-animated memories that piece together the subway’s tragedy. 
Player Roles
Human (The Commuter)
Controls machinery, switches, and physical obstacles.
Uses a flashlight beam to reveal hidden runes during merges.
Vulnerable to darkness; must rely on the Ghost’s guidance.


Ghost (The Wanderer)
Phases through thin walls and ghost gates.
Reveals hidden inscriptions and frozen time echoes.
Loses visibility of the world when too far from the Human.
Only by staying within the Afterlight Field — the overlapping aura that appears during the merge — can both survive.
Structure and Progression
Level format: Station → Tunnel → Service Room → Platform Boss or Memory Sequence.


Each level’s puzzle revolves around the interplay of two realities (for example, Human repairs power while Ghost guides through a dark maze).


Between nights, players rest in a “Safe Carriage” hub to view collected Echo Fragments and upgrade shared abilities such as light radius and merge duration.


Art and Tone
Pixel art with modern lighting (URP 2D Lights, bloom, parallax).


Deep blues, greys, and violets with bursts of gold during merges.


Melancholy yet hopeful mood — a liminal mix of cyberpunk and ghost story.

Audio Direction
Lo-fi ambience of trains, dripping water, and distant announcers.


Piano and ambient synth soundtrack that swells during merges.


Sound design uses subtle reverb differences to show which world you’re in.
Technical and Steam Features
Online co-op using Steam Networking Sockets (Invite Friend flow).


Steam Cloud saves host progress and player settings.


Steam Input support for controllers and Steam Deck.


Playtest branch for early multiplayer testing.


Expansion Ideas
Merge Mishaps: random anomalies where worlds collide early or late.


A secret “Conductor” NPC who manipulates merges.


Branching endings based on how many Echo Fragments are restored.


Tagline and One-Sentence Pitch
“Two souls. Two worlds. Sixty seconds to connect.”
 Afterlight Metro is a pixel-art co-op adventure where a living commuter and a ghost work together between midnight trains to escape a city that never sleeps. 




PUZZLES:

Spectral wiring: Human has to connect wires together with the help of the ghost who is able to see the flow of energy from the wires.
Patrolling Guard: Human has to navigate through a specific area of the metro without being spotted by the guard. Ghost will tell human which ways to go to not get caught. Takes place in a darker area. 




